SIMPLE: propagate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Propagate
<hw>Prop"a*gate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Propagated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Propagating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>propagatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>propagare</ets> to propagate, akin
to <ets>propages</ets>, <ets>propago</ets>, a layer of a plant, slip,
shoot. See <er>Pro-</er>, and cf. <er>Pact</er>, <er>Prop</er>,
<er>Prune</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to continue or multiply by generation, or
successive production; -- applied to animals and plants; <as>as, to
<ex>propagate</ex> a breed of horses or sheep; to <ex>propagate</ex> a
species of fruit tree.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cause to spread to extend; to impel or continue
forward in space; <as>as, to <ex>propagate</ex> sound or
light</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To spread from person to person; to extend the
knowledge of; to originate and spread; to carry from place to place; to
disseminate; <as>as, to <ex>propagate</ex> a story or report; to
<ex>propagate</ex> the Christian religion.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The infection was <qex>propagated</qex> insensibly.</q>
<rj><qau>De Foe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To multiply; to increase.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Griefs of mine own lie heavy in my breast,⟦br⟧
Which thou wilt <qex>propagate</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To generate; to produce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Motion <qex>propagated</qex> motion, and life threw off life.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To multiply; continue; increase; spread; diffuse;
disseminate; promote.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Propagate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Propagate
<hw>Prop"a*gate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To have young or issue; to
be produced or multiplied by generation, or by new shoots or plants;
<as>as, rabbits <ex>propagate</ex> rapidly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No need that thou⟦br⟧
Should'st <qex>propagate</qex>, already infinite.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Propagation</ent>⟦br⟧
